| Wal-Mart Begins Massive Push For HD DVD                            |
|   from the 200-bucks-by-Christmas dept.                            |
|   posted by kdawson on Saturday April 21, @21:52 (Media)           |
|   http://hardware.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/04/22/0035238     |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

Several readers sent us word of [0]Wal-Mart's ordering 2 million HD DVD
players from China. [1]Hans V wrote, "My kids work at Wal-Mart and the
manager there has been talking about this. HD-DVD's are selling like mad
there so I hear." Another reader sent us a few links in Chinese and
summarized them this way: "The first batches of these blue-laser HD DVD
players are to land sometime in 2007, with complete fulfillment of the
order [from Fuh Yuan] in 2008. The deal could be worth up to $300 million
US, which translates to $150 per player. If so, by the time Christmas
2007 rolls around, Wal-Mart could be selling these for less than $200
retail, although some speculate that the initial manufacturer suggested
retail pricing might be in the ballpark of $299. Currently the cheapest
high-definition player is a Toshiba HD DVD with an MSRP of $399." By
comparison Blu-Ray players, manufactured in Japan, are not expected to
drop below $1000 until next year. The International Herald Tribune writes
about the [2]risk Toshiba is taking by bringing in Chinese manufacturers
to trump Sony in the format war.

Discuss this story at:
    http://hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/04/22/0035238

Links:
    0. http://gizmodo.com/gadgets/home-entertainment/wal+mart-makes-the-push-for-299-hd-dvd-machines-253950.php
    1. mailto:hansvadm@shaw.ca
    2. http://www.iht.com/articles/2005/10/20/business/dvd.php


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Safeguards For RIAA Hard Drive Inspection                          |
|   from the under-watchful-eyes dept.                               |
|   posted by kdawson on Saturday April 21, @23:54 (Music)           |
|   http://yro.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/04/22/0045222          |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]NewYorkCountryLawyer writes "In [1]SONY v. Arellanes, an RIAA case in
Sherman, Texas, [2]the Court entered a [3]protective order (PDF) that
spells out the following procedure for the RIAA's examination of the
defendant's hard drive: (1) RIAA imaging specialist makes mirror image of
hard drive; (2) mutually acceptable computer forensics expert makes make
two verified bit images, and creates an MD5 or equivalent hash code; (3)
one mirror image is held in escrow by the expert, the other given to
defendant's lawyer for a 'privilege review'; (4) defendant's lawyer
provides plaintiffs' lawyer with a 'privilege log' (list of privileged
files); (5) after privilege questions are resolved, the escrowed image —
with privileged files deleted — will be turned over to RIAA lawyers, to
be held for 'lawyers' eyes only.' The order differs from the [4]earlier
[5]order (PDF) entered in the case, in that it (a) permits the RIAA's own
imaging person to make the initial mirror image and (b) spells out the
details of the method for safeguarding privilege and privacy."

Discuss this story at:
    http://yro.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/04/22/0045222

Links:
    0. http://recordingindustryvspeople.blogspot.com/
    1. http://recordingindustryvspeople.blogspot.com/#SONY_v_Arellanes
    2. http://recordingindustryvspeople.blogspot.com/2007/04/judge-in-sony-v-arellanes-modifies.html
    3. http://info.riaalawsuits.us/sony_arellanes_070314OrderReconsiderationHardDrive.pdf
    4. http://yro.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=06/10/27/1912204&tid=141
    5. http://info.riaalawsuits.us/sony_arellanes_061027orderharddriveinspection.pdf


